**Sec. 50101. Onshore Oil and Gas Leasing.**  
The Inflation Reduction Act’s onshore oil and gas royalty rates and noncompetitive leasing provisions are repealed, restoring pre-2022 rules. The Secretary of the Interior must immediately resume quarterly onshore lease sales in Wyoming, New Mexico, Colorado, Utah, Montana, North Dakota, Oklahoma, Nevada, and Alaska, with at least 50% of available parcels from resource management plans offered. Lease sales must be conducted within 18 months of an expression of interest, and the Secretary may not delay leasing due to pending resource management plan amendments. The term of a permit to drill is now a single, non-renewable 4-year period.

**Sec. 50102. Offshore Oil and Gas Leasing.**  
The Secretary of the Interior must conduct at least 30 region-wide lease sales in the Gulf of America by 2040, including one by December 15, 2025, and two annually from 2026 to 2039, with one held by March 15 and another by August 15 each year. In the Alaska Cook Inlet region, at least six lease sales must be held between 2026 and 2032, with one by March 15 each year. Lease terms for Gulf sales must match those of Lease Sale 254 (2020), with royalties set between 12.5% and 16.67%, and primary terms of 10 years for deepwater leases. For Alaska sales, 70% of revenues from 2034 onward go to the State of Alaska, and each sale must offer at least 1 million acres.

**Sec. 50103. Royalties on Extracted Methane.**  
Section 50263 of the Inflation Reduction Act, which imposed a methane royalty on extracted methane, is repealed, eliminating the tax on methane emissions from oil and gas operations.

**Sec. 50104. Alaska Oil and Gas Leasing.**  
The Secretary of the Interior must conduct at least four area-wide lease sales in the Coastal Plain by 2035, with the first within one year of enactment and subsequent sales every two years. Each sale must offer at least 400,000 acres of high-potential hydrocarbon areas, using terms from the 2020 Record of Decision. For fiscal years 2025–2033, 50% of receipts go to the State of Alaska; from 2034 onward, 70% go to the State, with the remainder to the Treasury.

**Sec. 50105. National Petroleum Reserve-Alaska.**  
The Secretary of the Interior must resume oil and gas lease sales under the NPR-A Program within 10 years of enactment, conducting at least five sales, each offering no fewer than 4 million acres. Lease terms, economic conditions, and stipulations must match those in the 2020 NPR-A Final Environmental Impact Statement and Record of Decision. Beginning in fiscal year 2034, 70% of lease receipts go to the State of Alaska, and 30% to the Treasury.

**Sec. 50201. Coal Leasing.**  
Within 90 days of enactment, the Secretary of the Interior must complete environmental reviews, set fair market value, hold lease sales, and award qualified coal leases to the highest bidders. Qualified applications pending or submitted within 90 days of enactment are prioritized, and the Secretary may grant mining approvals for existing leases.

**Sec. 50202. Coal Royalty.**  
The coal royalty rate is set at 12.5%, but capped at 7% through September 30, 2034. The change applies to all existing and new coal leases not yet terminated. Lessees who paid advance royalties before enactment receive a credit for the difference between the old and new royalty rates.

**Sec. 50203. Leases for Known Recoverable Coal Resources.**  
Within 90 days of enactment, the Secretary of the Interior must make available for lease at least 4 million additional acres of known recoverable coal resources on Federal land in the 48 contiguous States and Alaska, excluding lands in National Monuments, Wilderness, National Parks, and other protected designations.

**Sec. 50204. Authorization to Mine Federal Coal.**  
Federal coal reserves adjacent to State or private land may be mined if the mining plan was approved before enactment and would otherwise be uneconomical without access. The Secretary must authorize such mining within 90 days without substantial modification, subject to NEPA review.

**Sec. 50301. Timber Sales and Long-Term Contracting.**  
For fiscal years 2026–2034, the Forest Service must sell at least 250 million board-feet more timber annually than the prior year, up to the maximum allowable under forest plans. The Secretary must enter into at least 40 long-term contracts (20+ years) for national forest materials. The Bureau of Land Management must sell 20 million more board-feet annually and enter into at least 5 long-term contracts for vegetative materials, with all receipts deposited in the Treasury.

**Sec. 50302. Renewable Energy Fees on Federal Land.**  
The Secretary must collect annual acreage rent for wind and solar rights-of-way based on a formula: Per-Acre Rate × Encumbrance Factor × (1 + 3%)^Year of Term. A capacity fee equal to the greater of the acreage rent or 3.9% of electricity sales is also collected. Wind projects with over 25% multiple-use land may receive a 10% reduction in capacity fees.

**Sec. 50303. Renewable Energy Revenue Sharing.**  
Beginning January 1, 2026, 25% of renewable energy revenue from Federal land goes to the State where the project is located, and 25% is distributed to counties based on land contribution. Payments are made from the Treasury to States and counties in the following fiscal year and are in addition to payments in lieu of taxes.

**Sec. 50304. Rescission of National Park Service and BLM Funds.**  
Unobligated balances from Sections 50221, 50222, and 50223 of the Inflation Reduction Act are rescinded, totaling approximately $1.2 billion in previously allocated funds.

**Sec. 50305. Celebrating America's 250th Anniversary.**  
$150 million is appropriated to the National Park Service for events and activities commemorating the 250th anniversary of the founding of the United States, to remain available through fiscal year 2028.

**Sec. 50401. Strategic Petroleum Reserve.**  
$218 million is appropriated for maintenance and repairs of SPR storage and related facilities, and $171 million is allocated to purchase petroleum products for SPR storage, both to remain available until September 30, 2029. The mandate to draw down and sell SPR oil is repealed.

**Sec. 50402. Repeals; Resciissions.**  
Section 50142 of the Inflation Reduction Act is repealed, and its unobligated balance is rescinded. Additional unobligated balances from Sections 50123, 50141, 50144, 50145, 50151, 50152, 50153, and 50161 are also rescinded, totaling over $1.5 billion in rescinded funds.

**Sec. 50403. Energy Dominance Financing.**  
The Energy Policy Act of 2005 is amended to allow funding for grid reliability, energy system adequacy, and critical minerals. The commitment authority is extended to 2028. $1 billion is appropriated for fiscal year 2025, with up to 3% for administrative costs.

**Sec. 50404. Transformational Artificial Intelligence Models.**  
The Secretary of Energy must mobilize National Laboratories to curate and preprocess DOE scientific data for AI/ML use and initiate seed projects for self-improving AI models. These models will accelerate innovation in microelectronics and new energy technologies. $150 million is appropriated for this effort, to remain available through September 30, 2026.

**Sec. 50501. Water Conveyance and Surface Water Storage Enhancement.**  
$1 billion is appropriated to the Bureau of Reclamation for upgrading existing conveyance and storage facilities, with no matching or cost-sharing requirements. Funds may be used for construction and associated activities, and contracts are not treated as new or amended under Reclamation laws. Funds remain available through September 30, 2034. [end of text]


